classitems.description:
isStr

Returns true if passed param is EITHER a simple string OR a 'string object' - otherwise returns false

str

Returns a simple string if the passed param is EITHER a simple string OR a 'string object',
 else returns the original object

min / max

Alias for Math.min/.max to simplify coding

transformData

Processes the options passed in and transforms them into the format used by layout()
Missing keys are added, and converts the data if passed in 'flat-format' (no sub-keys)
In flat-format, pane-specific-settings are prefixed like: north__optName  (2-underscores)
To update effects, options MUST use nested-keys format, with an effects key

params.name: JSON
params.description: d  Data/options passed by user - may be a single level or nested levels

return.description: JSON  Creates a data struture that perfectly matches 'options', ready to be imported

classitems.description:

Set an INTERNAL callback to avoid simultaneous animation
Runs only if needed and only if all callbacks are not 'already set'!

params.name: String
params.description: action  Either 'open' or 'close'

classitems.pane: Boolean  param   Extra param for callback (optional)

RUN the INTERNAL callback for this pane - if one exists

params.description: action  Either 'open' or 'close'

classitems.pane: Boolean  param   Extra param for callback (optional)

classitems.description:
cssW / cssH / cssSize

Contains logic to check boxModel & browser, and return the correct width/height for the current browser/doctype

params.name: Variant
params.description: elem  Can accept a 'pane' (east, west, etc) OR a DOM object OR a jQuery object

params.name: Integer
params.description: outerWidth/outerHeight  (optional) Can pass a width, allowing calculations BEFORE element is resized

return.description: Integer  Returns the innerHeight of the elem by subtracting padding and borders

todo: May need to add additional logic to handle more browser/doctype variations?

getPaneSize

Calculates the current 'size' (width or height) of a border-pane - optionally with 'pane spacing' added

return.description: Integer  Returns EITHER Width for east/west panes OR Height for north/south panes - adjusted for boxModel & browser

classitems.description:
getPaneDims

Returns data for setting the size/position of center pane. Date is also used to set Height for east/west panes

return.description: JSON  Returns a hash of all dimensions: top, bottom, left, right, (outer) width and (outer) height

classitems.description:
getElemDims

Returns data for setting size of an element (container or a pane).
classitems.callers: create(), onWindowResize() for container, plus others for pane

return.description: JSON  Returns a hash of all dimensions: top, bottom, left, right, outerWidth, innerHeight, etc

classitems.description:
addPinBtn

Add a custom Pin button for a pane

Four classes are added to the element, based on the paneClass for the associated pane...
Assuming the default paneClass and the pin is 'up', these classes are added for a west-pane pin:
 - ui-layout-pane-pin
 - ui-layout-pane-west-pin
 - ui-layout-pane-pin-up
 - ui-layout-pane-west-pin-up

classitems.description:
Sets the type of metadata to use. Metadata is encoded in JSON, and each property
in the JSON will become a property of the element itself.

There are three supported types of metadata storage:

  attr:  Inside an attribute. The name parameter indicates *which* attribute.
         
  class: Inside the class attribute, wrapped in curly braces: { }
  
  elem:  Inside a child element (e.g. a script tag). The
         name parameter indicates *which* element.
         
The metadata for an element is loaded the first time the element is accessed via jQuery.

As a result, you can define the metadata type, use $(expr) to load the metadata into the elements
matched by expr, then redefine the metadata type and run another $(expr) for other elements.
classitems.name: $.meta.setType

Missing item type
Sets the type of metadata to use. Metadata is encoded in JSON, and each property
in the JSON will become a property of the element itself.

There are three supported types of metadata storage:

  attr:  Inside an attribute. The name parameter indicates *which* attribute.
         
  class: Inside the class attribute, wrapped in curly braces: { }
  
  elem:  Inside a child element (e.g. a script tag). The
         name parameter indicates *which* element.
         
The metadata for an element is loaded the first time the element is accessed via jQuery.

As a result, you can define the metadata type, use $(expr) to load the metadata into the elements
matched by expr, then redefine the metadata type and run another $(expr) for other elements.

Missing item type
Returns the metadata object for the first member of the jQuery object.
